+# Exploration 002 Summary
+
+## Goal
+
+Freeze the exact search object and support class for Chain Step 2, together
+with the recursive closure convention, spectator inclusion rule, admissible
+enlargements, smallest-first ordering, and escalation ladder.
+
+## What I Tried
+
+- Read the Step-1 chain brief, refined/winning chain notes, and the attack /
+  judgment material that sharpened the closure and ordering requirements.
+- Pulled the predecessor mission's support and canonicalization notes only for
+  representation discipline, not as the search object itself.
+- Froze one exact search class, one recursive closure rule, one spectator
+  policy, two admissible enlargement rules, one lexicographic ordering, and one
+  concrete escalation ladder.
+
+## Outcome
+
+`succeeded`
+
+## One Key Takeaway
+
+Step 2 should enumerate **finite helical mode supports** with mandatory
+conjugate completion and recursive exact closure; packet families may still be
+used as seed templates, but not as the primary search object, and every
+closure-forced spectator mode belongs in the exact support ledger from the
+start.
+
+## Leads Worth Pursuing
+
+- Start the Step-2 ladder at one exact triad orbit, then shared-mode two-triad
+  and three-triad clusters before raising the seed budget.
+- Use one admissible enlargement test on every apparent survivor so later
+  locking claims are not artifacts of over-pruning.
+- Track the size of the closure-forced spectator ledger as part of the support
+  audit itself, not as a later dynamics-only metric.
+
+## Unexpected Findings
+
+- The predecessor mission's packet-support notes remain useful mainly as a
+  warning about canonicalization tiers; they do not justify packet-level search
+  objects here.
+- Helical sign data is not disposable bookkeeping for this branch because the
+  mission's phase/coherence object and exact coefficient law both depend on it.
+
+## Computations Worth Doing Later
+
+- Run the first-budget closure audit explicitly on one-triad and two-triad seed
+  classes using the frozen recursive rule.
+- Compare fixed-point sizes and spectator burdens across the first two ladder
+  levels before escalating the seed budget.
